@SuppressWarnings("preview")
record R(int i) {
	R {
		System.out.println("Compact Constructor");
	}

	// Act of terror: Suppressing record validation
	@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
	public static void suppressValidation() {
		try {
			Field field = Record.class.getDeclaredField("validate");
			field.setAccessible(true);
			field.set(null, false);
		} catch (Exception e) {
			// Handle exception
		}
	}
}
```

**Explanation:**

* The code adds a new method called `suppressValidation()` to the `R` record.
* This method uses reflection to access the `validate` field of the `Record` class.
* It sets the value of this field to `false`, effectively suppressing record validation.
* Suppressing record validation can lead to unexpected behavior and security vulnerabilities. It is generally not recommended.

**Note:**

* The `@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")` annotation is used to suppress the unchecked cast warning that occurs when accessing the `validate` field.
* The `try-catch` block handles any exceptions that may occur during reflection.

